  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several international laws and conventions aimed at preventing money laundering. Some key examples include:\n\n1. United Nations Conventions\n- UN Convention against Transnational Organized Crime\n- UN Convention against Corruption\n\n2. Financial Action Task Force (FATF) Recommendations\n- International standards for combating money laundering\n- Adopted by over 190 countries and jurisdictions\n\n3. International Monetary Fund (IMF) Guidelines\n- Provide frameworks for preventing financial crimes\n\n4. Basel Committee on Banking Supervision Standards\n- Establishes global banking regulations\n\n5. Specific Regional Agreements\n- European Union's Anti-Money Laundering Directives\n- OECD Anti-Bribery Convention\n\nThese laws typically require countries to:\n- Criminalize money laundering\n- Implement reporting requirements\n- Establish financial intelligence units\n- Conduct customer due diligence\n- Share information across borders\n- Impose penalties for non-compliance\n\nIndividual countries also have their own national laws implementing these international standards, such as the Bank Secrecy Act in the United States and the Proceeds of Crime Act in the United Kingdom.",
